commits.message:
Add --defs-yaml-template flag to DG CLI inspect-component command

## Summary & Motivation

Adds a new `--defs-yaml-template` flag to the `dg utils inspect-component` command that generates comprehensive YAML templates for component definition files. This feature helps developers understand component structure by providing both schema documentation and example values in a single output.

The template generator creates structured YAML with:
- Schema documentation section with field types, requirements, and descriptions
- Example values section with valid YAML using realistic sample data
- Support for complex nested objects, arrays, and schema references
- Automatic handling of optional vs required fields

Example usage:
```bash
dg utils inspect-component dagster_dbt.DbtProjectComponent --defs-yaml-template
```

This complements the existing `--component-schema` flag by providing a more user-friendly format that developers can directly copy and modify for their component configurations.

## How I Tested These Changes

Added comprehensive unit tests covering the new flag functionality, template generation for various component types, and validation that prevents multiple flags from being used simultaneously. Existing test suite continues to pass.

## Changelog

[DG CLI] Added `--defs-yaml-template` flag to `dg utils inspect-component` command to generate comprehensive YAML templates for component definition files.

# Refactor cantilever demo into instructional functional modules for numerical methods learning ## Summary This PR refactors the cantilever beam demonstration script to better highlight key numerical methods concepts for beginners. The original linear script has been reorganized into clear functional modules that map directly to the fundamental stages of finite element analysis: - **Geometry**: `make_geometry()` - defines beam dimensions in 3D space - **Discretization**: `discretize()` - creates hexahedral mesh and vector function space - **Boundary Conditions**: `apply_boundary_conditions()` - enforces clamped constraints - **Matrix Construction**: `build_forms()` + `assemble_system()` - separates form definition from assembly - **Linear Solver**: `solve_system()` - explicit PETSc KSP configuration and solving - **Analysis & Results**: `analyze_and_export()` - strain/stress computation and visualization output **Key Technical Change**: Replaced `LinearProblem` with explicit matrix assembly (`fem_petsc.assemble_matrix`/`assemble_vector`) and PETSc KSP solver to clearly separate "matrix construction" from "linear solver" stages as requested for educational purposes. ## Review & Testing Checklist for Human - [ ] **End-to-end execution test**: Run `python python/demo/demo_cantilever_beam.py` from repo root and verify it completes without errors - [ ] **Numerical correctness**: Check that displacement norm and solution patterns are reasonable for a cantilever beam - [ ] **Educational clarity**: Verify the functional decomposition makes the numerical methods pipeline clear and easy to follow - [ ] **Solver verification**: Confirm the PETSc KSP configuration (`preonly`/`lu`) works correctly and converges - [ ] **Visualization outputs**: Open generated XDMF files in ParaView to verify beam deflection and stress patterns look physically correct **Recommended test plan**: Execute the demo, then load `out_cantilever/*.xdmf` in ParaView to visually inspect that the cantilever shows expected deflection (max at free end) and stress distribution (tension/compression on opposite faces). --- ### Diagram ```mermaid %%{ init : { "theme" : "default" }}%% graph TD DemoFile["python/demo/

issue.title: AndroidX considering dropping support for .pom files
issue.body:
AndroidX is considering dropping support for `.pom` files and just using `.module`. `.pom` files do not really work with KMP, where there is no such thing as a single artifact, it all depends on the consumer, e.g. if the consumer if JVM vs Android you get a different artifact. AndroidX KMP usage is growing, and we keep putting in really ugly workarounds in our build to keep .pom files barely usable (e.g. https://github.com/bazel-contrib/rules_jvm_external/issues/864). The maintenance burden has really reached a tipping point.

This change would be a no-op for our Gradle users, but likely breaking for alternative build system users (e.g Bazel, Buck, etc).

I can see that Bazel is looking to support Gradle resolver (https://github.com/bazel-contrib/rules_jvm_external/pull/1357)
instead of using poms. This change would be required for all the bazel users to keep consuming AndroidX artifacts.

We would obviously give an x month heads up to the world when we do this change.

I wanted to create this issue to start the discussion.

commits.message:
Add isolation test for TOAST value reuse during CLUSTER

This test exercises the corner case in toast_save_datum() where CLUSTER
operations encounter duplicated TOAST references, reusing the existing
TOAST data instead of creating redundant copies.

During table rewrites like CLUSTER, both live and recently-dead versions
of a row may reference the same TOAST value.  When copying the second or
later version of such a row, the system checks if a TOAST value already
exists in the new TOAST table using toastrel_valueid_exists().  If
found, toast_save_datum() sets data_todo = 0 so as redundant data is not
stored, ensuring only one copy of the TOAST value exists in the new
table.

The test relies on a combination of UPDATE, CLUSTER, and checks of the
TOAST values used before and after the relation rewrite, to make sure
that the same values are reused across the rewrite.

This is a continuation of 69f75d671475 to make sure that this corner
case keeps working should we mess with this area of the code.

Author: Nikhil Kumar Veldanda <veldanda.nikhilkumar17@gmail.com>
Discussion: https://postgr.es/m/CAFAfj_E+kw5P713S8_jZyVgQAGVFfzFiTUJPrgo-TTtJJoazQw@mail.gmail.com

Update obsolete comments in ResultRelInfo struct.

Commit c5b7ba4e6 changed things so that the ri_RootResultRelInfo field
of this struct is set for both partitions and inheritance children and
used for tuple routing and transition capture (before that commit, it
was only set for partitions to route tuples into), but failed to update
these comments.

Author: Etsuro Fujita <etsuro.fujita@gmail.com>
Reviewed-by: Dean Rasheed <dean.a.rasheed@gmail.com>
Discussion: https://postgr.es/m/CAPmGK14NF5CcdCmTZpxrvpvBiT0y4EqKikW1r_wAu1CEHeOmUA%40mail.gmail.com
Backpatch-through: 14

Add support for extensions with an owned schema

Writing the sql migration scripts that are run by CREATE EXTENSION and
ALTER EXTENSION UPDATE are security minefields for extension authors.
One big reason for this is that search_path is set to the schema of the
extension while running these scripts, and thus if a user with lower
privileges can create functions or operators in that schema they can do
all kinds of search_path confusion attacks if not every function and
operator that is used in the script is schema qualified. While doing
such schema qualification is possible, it relies on the author to never
make a mistake in any of the sql files. And sadly humans have a tendency
to make mistakes.

This patch adds a new "owned_schema" option to the extension control
file that can be set to true to indicate that this extension wants to
own the schema in which it is installed. What that means is that the
schema should not exist before creating the extension, and will be
created during extension creation. This thus gives the extension author
an easy way to use a safe search_path, while still allowing all objects
to be grouped together in a schema. The implementation also has the
pleasant side effect that the schema will be automatically dropped when
the extension is dropped.

issue.body:
# Add cantilever beam stress-strain analysis demos for DOLFINx ## Summary This PR adds comprehensive demonstration scripts for simulating stress-strain distribution in a cantilevered beam with end load using DOLFINx. The main contribution is an **educational refactoring** that separates the finite element analysis workflow into 6 clear functional abstractions, making it highly instructive for learning numerical methods, plus comprehensive mathematical documentation. **Key additions:** - `educational_cantilever_demo.py`: **NEW** - Refactored demo with clear 6-stage functional abstractions for learning numerical methods - `README_CANTILEVER_DEMO.md`: **NEW** - Complete mathematical formulation from PDEs to matrix systems -
